<TEXT>
yale university researchers working with the 
national institutes of health say they are optimistic that a 
methadone substitute they discovered will prove more effective in 
getting heroin addicts off all drugs 
if true it could have a significantly help curb the spread of 
aids among drug abusers and their sexual partners 
thomas r kosten and associates at the universitys school of 
medicine are conducting a sixmonth study with 120 subjects to see 
whether they can duplicate the promising results from a onemonth 
pilot study involving 41 addicts 
i think this can be a major treatment advance for us in 
working with these drug addicts who are spreading aids on the 
streets kosten said wednesday at a seminar 
aids or acquired immune deficiency syndrome is a contagious 
disease that attacks the bodys immune system rendering it 
incapable of resisting other diseases and infections the virus 
most often is spread through close contact with blood blood 
products or semen from infected persons 
it is now spreading faster among intravenous drug abusers than 
any other segment of the population because of their tendency to 
share needles that have traces of another persons blood on them 
the presidents aids commission concluded that curbing 
intravenous drug abuse and having a federal law barring 
discrimination against people with the aids virus are the two 
main keys to fighting the epidemic that threatens to kill a million 
or more people already believed to be infected 
the drug kosten is working with is buprenorphine which has been 
used in europe for about 10 years as a prescription pain reliever 
although not in drug treatment programs 
the pilot study by kosten and herbert d kleber financed by the 
national institute on drug abuse found that buprenorphine was as 
effective as methadone at blunting the subjects craving for heroin 
but unlike heroin or methadone buprenorphine appears to be 
virtually nonaddicting and does not pose the risk of overdose 
said kosten 
the biggest potential payoff however is that the pilot test 
subjects did not experience the severe withdrawal symptoms common 
to users of heroin and methadone when either drug is stopped 
what we are going for eventually is to get people drug free 
and that is a problem with methadone said kosten 
a longstanding criticism of methadone treatment is that it 
essentially switches one addiction for another albeit to a legal 
one normally administered in a controlled setting 
but kosten noted that the potential for methadone abuse is 
not nil 
although methadone is normally dissolved and taken in liquid 
form under observation at drug treatment centers it also sometimes 
is illicitly injected as a street substitute for heroin 
although it is possible buprenorphine could be injected in 
nonclinical settings it appears to open a new avenue to weaning 
addicts from the physical trauma of withdrawal from either heroin 
or methadone 
the idea is to eliminate the withdrawal hurdle making it easier 
for addicts to get off all injectable drugs and eliminate their 
continued exposure to aidscontaminated needles 
</TEXT>
