communist party said it would abstain 
the proposal needed 316 votes to pass 
the christian democrat leader staked his 6monthold coalition 
on the reform measure which is aimed at eliminating one of the 
principal causes of italys government instability 
de mita indicated last week that he would resign if the measure 
was rejected socialist leader bettino craxi whose party is the 
second largest in the coalition after the christian democrats 
pushed hard for passage 
the senate will now take up the reform measure 
italy was one of the few western democracies where most 
parliamentary votes were secret and citizens had no certainty about 
how their representatives voted on issues 
the open vote is expected to strengthen the executive system and 
create a more stable political climate in a country that has had a 
succession of revolingdoor governments de mitas is italys 48th 
postwar government 
previously governments have been plagued by lawmakers who used 
the secret ballot to vote against their party line particularly to 
ensure passage of pet spending projects 
de mitas predecessor giovanni goria resigned after his 
government was repeatedly defeated in attempts to trim italys 
budget deficit which now stands at 87 billion 
the communists who had wanted to limit open voting to financial 
measures said they would abstain in an attempt to show up 
government party deputies who vote against their own coalition 
the five parties have 377 seats in the 630seat chamber of 
deputies 
under the chambers reform voting still will be secret when 
dealing with special government bodies such as the organized crime 
commission when the vote involves a specific person or when it 
deals with such issues as abortion or personal liberties proposed 
substantive changes to the constitution also be would excluded from 
open ballots 
but the majority of chamber votes especially on financial 
issues such as the annual budget will be open 
