<DOCNO> AP881013-0119 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
even moderate use of cocaine during the first 
three months of pregnancy may lead to an increased risk of 
spontaneous abortion and premature birth a researcher says 
the longterm effects of this socalled recreational use of 
cocaine early during pregnancy are not yet known said dr kenneth 
jones a birth defects specialist at the university of california 
san diego 
earlier studies of women who use cocaine heavily often in 
combination with other drugs suggest that cocaine can produce 
abnormal behavior in 3dayold infants and can lead to increased 
risk of bleeding in the brain which may or may not be related to 
the behavioral difficulties jones said wednesday night at the 
annual meeting in new orleans of the american society of human 
genetics 
these are the most important things we know about prenatal 
cocaine we dont know how they the infants are going to do when 
they grow up he said in an interview to label them 
neurological cripples is unfair 
the infants show irritability and emotional distress when 
handled or dressed jones said adding that standard tests to 
assess their health show that the infants have an impaired ability 
to interact with their environment 
in his ongoing study of modest cocaine users those who said 
they used less than one gram of cocaine per week and said they used 
no other drugs jones found that 17 of the 73 women or 23 
percent had spontaneous abortions 
thirteen women or 18 percent gave birth prematurely 
jones emphasized that the results are preliminary and that the 
study has not been subjected to the scientific scrutiny that 
customarily takes place before an article is accepted for 
publication in a medical journal 
studies of heavy cocaine users have shown that they often 
experience detachment of the placenta from the uterus which can 
produce spontaneous abortion if it occurs early in pregnancy or can 
produce abrupt birth if it occurs later in pregnancy 
this detachment and the behavioral problems associated with 
cocaine use in pregnancy might all be consequences of the effects 
cocaine has on the blood vessels jones said 
cocaine causes the blood vessels to tighten and narrow and 
results in an increase in blood pressure these changes could 
trigger placenta separation and bleeding in the brain jones said 
further studies are necessary to assess these problems more 
carefully but such studies are difficult because many women who 
use cocaine also use other drugs and therefore it is difficult to 
determine precisely which problems are associated with cocaine 
rather than the other drugs jones said 
additionally because cocaine use is presumed to be harmful 
during pregnancy researchers may suffer from a subtle bias in 
which they seem to see more harm than can actually be proven to 
occur from cocaine use during pregnancy 
they may see things in the data that arent there he said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

