<TEXT>
the presidential press conference has fallen 
into a serious state of disarray under ronald reagan who has 
held relatively few such sessions a harvard commission says but 
reagans spokesman today said the report gave too much emphasis to 
how many sessions are held 
the panel of journalists and scholars urged the next president 
to take his lumps on a more frequent basis in its study on how 
to revive white house news conferences the panel also called for 
making them routine and mostly daytime events 
the longer presidents go without a press conference the 
greater the suspicion that there is something to hide and the 
greater the pressure becomes for holding press conferences the 
harvard commission on the presidential news conference said in a 
report wednesday 
when ultimately the president holds a conference it is 
liable to be a hostile affair in which both the president and the 
press look bad it would seem better on balance for the president 
to take his lumps on a more frequent basis 
asked today to respond to the reports criticism of the 
irregularity with which reagan has held news conferences white 
house spokesman marlin fitzwater defended the administrations 
record but he said i dont think any president in good 
conscience would ever commit to numbers on anything 
what im trying to say is that there is a diversity of 
ways to communicate with the general public besides a press 
conference fitzwater added weve held the press conferences 
that we think are appropriate weve held other kinds of press 
interviews that we think are useful and in the final analysis you 
can be the judge 
the commission also said that reporters must behave better the 
public will quit paying attention if it believes reporters 
questions are unfair irrelevant or overly aggressive it said 
the panel recommended that presidents meet with the media twice 
a month during daytime hours and limit televised evening news 
conferences to six a year 
daytime news conferences would reduce the temperature and 
encourage more substantive and useful exchanges the panel said 
the 16member commission appointed by the joan shorenstein 
barone center on the press politics and public policy of harvards 
john f kennedy school of government was cochaired by marvin 
kalb director of the center and frederick w mayer of duke 
university 
the commission said the presidential press conference a 
75yearold institution is not aging well 
once a forum for a vigorous exchange between the president and 
the press the institution has withered the panel said it is 
now in a serious state of disrepair 
the commission gave this history of the institution 
theodore roosevelt according to legend he invited some 
reporters who were waiting in the rain to come inside and hear him 
out the sessions however were not really news conferences the 
reporters simply stood and listened while the president talked to 
them often while being shaved by the white house barber 
woodrow wilson he initiated the news conference he felt 
presidents should be obliged to answer reporters questions just as 
british prime ministers field questions from the opposition in the 
house of commons 
warren harding wilsons successor met with the press twice a 
week for most of his presidency but required that the questions be 
submitted in advance in writing 
calvin coolidge if he didnt like a written question hed 
crumple it up and throw it away 
herbert hoover he met with reporters more than twice a week at 
the start but after the 1929 stock market crash he held less 
frequent short and uninformative meetings 
franklin d roosevelt he met in warm sessions with reporters 
almost twice a week for 13 years around his desk or at warm 
springs ga around his car he often flattered reporters 
impressed them with the depth of his knowledge sometimes bullied 
them once sent a reporter to sit in the corner wearing a dunce 
cap he didnt insist on written questions but sometimes put 
answers off the record and usually could only be paraphrased by 
reporters not quoted directly 
harry s truman he moved the press conference into a more 
formal setting most of what he said was on the record and 
sometimes his spunky spontaneous answers got him in trouble 
dwight d eisenhower he allowed television cameras in changing 
forever the nature of news conferences although live telecasts 
were not permitted 
john f kennedy his press conferences marked by wit became 
the standard against which subsequent presidents would be judged 
or judge themselves he had a briefing book prepared and 
practiced answers 
lyndon johnson kennedy was a tough act to follow and johnson 
to avoid questions when his vietnam policy came under challenge 
took to making long opening statements one study found his opening 
statements consumed more than a third of the time 
richard nixon he averaged only six a year during the watergate 
crisis when he went for five months without a press conference 
the press became so hostile that he once stalked off without 
awaiting the usual closing thank you mr president 
gerald ford he had difficulty dampening the press cynicism 
that had developed during the johnson and nixon administrations 
jimmy carter he kept to a twoamonth pledge for a year and a 
half but ended up averaging half that many holding fewer during 
the iran hostage crisis he moved them to the evening out of 
frustration with the way the television news shows edited his 
remarks at daytime news conferences 
reagan he pledged to hold news conferences once a month but 
has held only 45 in more than 7 years in office and once let 5 
months pass without one the president although successful in 
the short run in dodging difficult questions suffers from the 
perception that he is not really in charge of his own white house 
</TEXT>
