the us centers for disease control on thursday 
reported progress toward 1990 goals for childhood immunization but 
said adults are not showing up as they should for their shots 
phil horne program management officer for the cdcs 
immunization division said the problem is especially acute among 
the elderly 
in its weekly report the agency said 97 percent of the children 
entering kindergarten in 1986 had been immunized against 
diphtheria measles mumps whooping cough paralytic polio 
rubella and tetanus the goal was 95 percent 
the goal was 90 percent immunization against the same diseases 
for children 2 and under it appears likely that this objective 
will not be met the report said 
it said measles outbreaks among preschoolers although 
stabilized in recent years indicate the immunization level at that 
age is inadequate 
cdc figures show mumps in 1987 at the highest level since 1979 
with 12848 cases illinois and tennessee which had the highest 
number of cases did not start enforcing laws requiring preschool 
mumps immunization until 1987 and 1988 respectively 
the report said the 1990 target for reductions in diphtheria and 
polio appear to have been met and that there is substantial 
progress toward goals for tetanus and rubella 
school is the most forceful instrument we have now to assure 
immunization horne said but laws differ from state to state 
they are not consistent 
he said some states do not require some immunizations or may 
exempt some students on medical or religious grounds 
there is a general perception by the adult population that 
immunizations are childhood activities horne said there is a 
feeling that if they were immunized as a child they do not need to 
be immunized as adults 
he said only about 20 percent of the target population for 
influenza vaccines get the needed annual vaccinations and that 
about 10 percent of the target group has the onetimeonly 
pneumonia shot 
the target groups for both shots he said include people over 
65 or adults with any debilitating illness 
horne said the national coalition for adult immunizations 
formed out of concern for the adult vaccination figures is trying 
to get the word out through volunteer organizations and hopes to 
include its pitch with social security checks 
he said it is difficult to measure success 
with school enterers we can require a statement of proof of 
immunization for entry into school he said most industries 
would not require a similar statement for example for new 
employees 
vaccinations of target groups for hepatitis b he said range 
from an estimated 5 percent to 40 percent to 50 percent with the 
high end including health care professionals such as dentists and 
those who handle human blood products 
the report identified users of illicit injectable drugs and 
homosexual men as target populations less likely to be vaccinated 
