<TEXT>
twentythree horses have died recently in 
the southern region of andalusia prompting fears of an epidemic 
that could force a change of venue of the equestrian events at the 
1992 olympic games 
the agriculture ministry said thursday that scores of sick 
horses have been tested to see if they have african horse sickness 
but results are not expected until next week if they are found to 
have the disease it would be the second outbreak in 14 months in 
spain 
the ministry said the government has taken the precaution of 
importing 7500 doses of vaccine for african horse sickness from 
south africa where the illness is endemic 
gerard de las casas a government health official from 
andalusia said preliminary tests of 150 sick horses turned up 
negative results for the disease but he said the horses are so 
sick they will have to be put to death 
de las casas said the regional government has prohibited entry 
into southern spain of horses from north africa as well as the 
movement of all horses within the andalusian region 
african horse sickness is also known as equine plague it is a 
viral disease transmitted by insects symptoms include fever and 
fluid retention and death may occur quickly from fluidfilled 
lungs there is no known cure but vaccinations have proved 
effective 
the madrid daily el pais quoted a spanish olympic committee 
official as saying that another outbreak of the illness could 
result in spain being cited as a country where the disease is 
endemic 
the 1992 summer olympic games are to be held in barcelona 
the official who was not identified was quoted as saying that 
an outbreak could force the equestrian events to be held elsewhere 
since equestrians would not want to bring horses to a country where 
the disease is endemic 
the last outbreak of african horse disease in spain occurred in 
august 1987 in central spain 
the most recent horse deaths occurred last week at the swank 
sotogrande resort in cadiz province and in eight sites in 
neighboring malaga province the agriculture ministry said 
the andalusia government said thursday it canceled a special 
show of andalusian horses set for seville during the oct 1721 
state visit of queen elizabeth ii the first state visit to spain 
by a british monarch 
</TEXT>
