<TEXT>
china will freeze or impose ceilings on the 
prices of a wide range of goods to curb rising inflation the 
official xinhua news agency reported thursday 
it was the first government indication that it will actually 
roll back price reforms rather than merely halting them as 
previously announced 
the situation in the last month shows that the prices of some 
commodities have not yet been reined in xinhua quoted cheng 
zhiping director of the state administration of commodity prices 
as saying 
he said the government will establish national price ceilings 
for important means of production and freeze the prices of 
daily necessities that previously were decontrolled xinhua did 
not list the affected items 
price ceilings will be set for grain now sold on the free 
market and the prices of chemical fertilizer pesticides and other 
agricultural inputs will be regulated xinhua quoted cheng as 
saying 
cheng spoke two weeks after the ruling communist party ordered a 
twoyear effort to control inflation officially estimated at about 
20 percent but believed to be higher the party called for steps to 
end hoarding profiteering and loose credit that have fueled 
inflation and for a cutback in industrial growth that has strained 
the countrys weak infrastructure 
premier li peng on tuesday ordered the state council chinas 
cabinet to put the new austerity policy into effect 
nobody can shirk responsiblity and the problems cannot be left 
unsettled xinhua quoted him as saying he said soaring prices 
are affecting social security and peoples confidence in 
reform and that a period of stability is needed 
a series of xinhua reports thursday indicated the government 
envisions a widescale retrenchment in its decadeold process of 
reducing central controls over the economy 
one report quoted commerce minister hu ping as saying the retail 
price of major commodities will be standardized many commodities 
deemed essential such as soap currently float within locally set 
ranges while hundreds of other light industrial items are 
completely decontrolled 
hu also was quoted as saying the government will seek to 
stablize the prices of nonstaple foods most of which now sell on 
the free market at prices set by local supply and demand again 
xinhua gave no specific list of goods affected or the level at 
which prices would be held 
xinhua also gave no date for enacting the measures announced by 
cheng and hu 
economists generally believe that decontrol of prices so they 
can reflect supply and demand is essential to chinas effort to 
replace cumbersome central planning with a more flexible 
marketstyle economy however chinas price reform has been 
piecemeal resulting in a hodgepodge of controlled 
semicontrolled and decontrolled prices 
some goods are sold both by the state at artifically low prices 
and on the free market at much higher prices resulting in growing 
profiteering li and other top officials recently said this mix of 
prices will remain for a long time 
liu hongru deputy governor of the peoples bank of china the 
central bank meanwhile reported a drop in the money supply since 
late september and slowdown in new loan issues xinhua quoted liu 
as saying both developments indicated that government moves to 
tighten loose credit were taking effect 
</TEXT>
