<TEXT>
the nations merchandise trade deficit surged 
to 1218 billion in august as a record flood of imported products 
swamped a continued boom in exports the government reported 
thursday 
the commerce department said the august imbalance was 27 
billion higher than the july figure which had been the lowest 
monthly deficit in 3 years 
while the august figure was slightly worse than expected 
financial markets took the news in stride unlike a year ago when a 
disappointing trade report set off a chain of events culminating in 
the oct 19 stock market collapse 
the dollar tumbled briefly in hectic foreign exchange trading 
but then steadied the dow jones average of 30 industrial stocks 
gained 712 points to close at 213336 
the market reaction was in sharp contrast to a year ago when 
the august trade report sent the dow plunging by 95 points setting 
the stage for the record 508point drop five days later on black 
monday 
analysts said the market got the bad news out of the way early 
this time falling by more than 30 points on wednesday on fears 
that the report would show a higher trade deficit 
the reagan administration which has been fending off attacks on 
its trade record by democratic presidential candidate michael 
dukakis and running mate lloyd bentsen moved quickly to play down 
the significance of the widening in the august deficit 
commerce secretary c william verity noted that the trade 
deficit for the first eight months of the year is running at an 
annual rate of 1385 billion a 19 percent improvement from the 
record deficit of 1703 billion run up in 1987 
i have been saying for some time now that we can hope for an 
improvement of about 30 billion in the trade deficit this year 
the figures for the first eight months show that we are right on 
target verity said 
however bentsen said the steep rise in the august deficit was 
another example of failed republican economic policies 
while imports flood america gop nominees george bush and 
dan quayle sit back and let the damage accumulate telling 
americans dont worry be happy 
senate majority leader robert byrd dwva said the august 
deficit was new evidence that the nations trade problems are far 
from being solved 
the longawaited light at the end of the tunnel has turned out 
to be an onrushing freight train loaded with imported goods said 
byrd this congress passed a comprehensive trade bill what 
we need is an administration that will enforce it 
in august both exports and imports climbed to record levels 
exports were up 103 billion to 2755 billion as america sold 
more cars business capital goods and farm products to foreigners 
the boom in export sales has lifted the fortunes of american 
manufacturing companies and is credited as the principal reason the 
country is enjoying betterthanexpected overall economic growth 
but imports rose even faster than exports in august surging by 
373 billion to an alltime high of 3972 billion 
private economists viewed the big jump in imports with concern 
they said it is unrealistic to expect further big increases in 
export levels which are up 29 percent so far this year from a year 
ago 
they said that for the trade deficit to shrink from the current 
level imports which are up 10 percent so far this year will have 
to begin to shrink 
the process of trade adjustment is slowing down said bruce 
steinberg senior economist at merrill lynch we made stellar 
gains in the first half of the year but we are going to make very 
little further progress for the rest of the year 
steinberg predicted that the trade deficit for this year would 
shrink by about 40 billion but that the decline in 1989 would be a 
much more modest 10 billion 
other analysts noted that foreign shipments of various types of 
consumer goods such as clothing shoes and electronics began 
rising in august as retailers faced with depleted inventories 
began placing new orders 
when you cut through all the monthtomonth fluctuations you 
are still left with a very large trade deficit said lawrence 
chimerine president of the wefa group an economic forecasting 
firm 
chimerine predicted that the dollar will have to fall further 
boosting prices of imported goods even more as a way of reducing 
american demand 
the import rise included a 11 billion increase in consumer 
goods and a similar advance in business capital goods reflecting 
higher demand for computers and electrical machinery 
car imports rose by 700 million in august while oil imports 
were up by 300 million to 37 billion as a jump in volume offset 
a drop in the price per barrel to 1515 
the 103 billion rise in us exports was attributed mainly to 
an increase of 800 million in sales of american cars and parts and 
a 200 million rise in the sales of farm goods 
as usual the largest single deficit was incurred with japan an 
imbalance of 48 billion up from a july deficit of 44 billion 
the united states recorded deficits of 17 billion with taiwan and 
14 billion with western europe 
