the house on thursday postponed until next 
week a vote on legislation that would establish disclosure 
requirements for banks department stores and other firms that 
offer credit cards 
the senatepassed measure requires that information to be 
provided in directmail solicitations include annual fees the 
interest rate charged for unpaid balances the method for 
calculating that balance and the length of grace periods during 
which no interest is charged similarly late fees overthelimit 
fees and fees for cash advances must be disclosed 
currently only a handful of states have laws requiring public 
disclosure of such information before consumers apply for the cards 
under an agreement the leadership gave to members no vote was 
to be taken in the house after 1 pm on thursday the bill got to 
the floor shortly before 2 pm and was discussed by house members 
a vote on the creditcard disclosure measure will be taken when 
the house returns from its weekend recess on tuesday 
rep fernand j st germain dri chairman of the house 
banking committee and the bills floor manager called the measure 
one of the most important and strongest credit disclosure acts 
that we have been able to move through the congress since the first 
truthinlending statute was passed 20 years ago 
he said the proposed law ends the hideandseek approach to 
disclosures on credit card terms it prevents sneak attacks on 
unsuspecting consumers who often learn of charges and fees long 
after the fact too late to reject the card and seek 
alternatives 
st germain said more than 100 million consumers have one or more 
credit cards with outstanding balances approaching 150 billion he 
also said credit card companies solicit nearly 25 billion 
consumers a year 
rep charles e schumer dny a chief house sponsor said 
millions of card users are not aware that there are tremendous 
differences between the costs of the credit cards available this 
should put an end to the unjustifiable rates of 18 19 or 20 
percent some card issuers are now able to charge 
the measure has been endorsed by a wide range of consumer groups 
but it has its opponents too 
rep frank annunzio dill chairman of the consumer 
subcommittee called the measure a bad bill disguised as a 
consumer protection bill it is fitting that we are taking up the 
bill in the month of halloween because this bill indeed wears a 
mask and unlike halloween where you at least get the option of 
trick or treat this bill offers only trick or trick 
among other things annunzio opposes the measure because it 
would prohibit states from enacting stricter standards and puts no 
limit on the amount of interest on outstanding balances that card 
issuers may charge 
let me suggest that what americans want in their credit cards 
is not more disclosure but lower interest rates on their 
charges he said there is nothing in this legislation that 
will cause credit interests to fall 
