a majority of adults believe schools should 
teach sex education and the federal government should put more 
money into development of new birth control methods according to a 
poll released thursday by planned parenthood federation of america 
the poll said 82 percent of the respondents favor government 
spending on research and development of new and improved birth 
control methods while 16 percent of those polled do not 
in addition 59 percent of those interviewed said they thought 
the europeandeveloped birth control pill ru 486 which can 
terminate a pregnancy in its first few weeks should be made 
available in this country thirtythree percent disagreed 
humphrey taylor president of louis harris said the poll also 
found that abortion is becoming a less controversial issue 
in 1979 38 percent said abortion was a decisive issue in 
choosing a candidate for elective office that number dropped in 
1982 to 28 percent and in 1988 to 18 percent of the 18 percent 9 
percent said they could not vote for a prochoice candidate and 9 
percent said they could not vote for an antiabortion candidate 
so one clear finding is that a lot of the heat is going out of 
the abortion issue and that political candidates in 1988 need not 
worry as much as they have in the past about losing votes on it 
one way or the other taylor said 
results of the poll conducted by louis harris and associates 
were released at the start of planned parenthoods annual meeting 
in st louis the findings were based on telephone interviews 
conducted in may with 1250 randomly selected adults nationwide 
the polls margin of error was 3 percent 
