that limpet mines and hand grenades found at the offices of the 
southern african bishops conference damaged in wednesdays fire 
came from the stocks of the police or army 
police said investigators were trying to determine the origin of 
the arms 
it does not matter from which quarter such callous deeds stem 
i want to give the assurance that the south african police will 
fight arson terrorism and violence with all the means available to 
it minister of law and order adriaan vlok said thursday night 
police said two mines two grenades and five ammunition 
magazines for sovietmade ak47 rifles were found after the 
predawn fire 
jude pieterse a spokesman for the bishops blamed the arsonists 
for planting the weapons 
there is no doubt that the objects of destruction were 
left in the building by the same persons who entered to destroy 
it pieterse said 
he said police investigators did not ask any questions about the 
explosives when speaking to church officials and workers 
we believe the reason for this omission is that the policemen 
assumed the explosives had been left by the saboteurs 
pieterse said 
no one was injured in the fire four people including a nun 
were rescued from a balcony where they were trapped by flames 
police said a minibus with false license plates was seen outside 
the building shortly before the fire started 
it was the second attack in six weeks on offices of an 
antiapartheid church organization a bomb wrecked the headquarters 
of the south african council of churches in johannesburg on aug 31 
the anc said the attacks on church groups reaffirm the immoral 
and criminal nature of the apartheid regime which falsely claims 
to be christian 
apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 
26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs the 5 million 
whites control the economy and maintain separate districts schools 
and health services 
elsewhere three black men were injured when a limpet mine 
exploded outside a post office in nigel about 30 miles southeast 
of johannesburg police said damage was minor police added 
police headquarters said six policemen were wounded by gunfire 
late wednesday in kathlehong a black township east of johannesburg 
the officers were hospitalized but were not seriously hurt 
police said 
no arrests were made police said cartridges found at the scene 
indicated the attackers used ak47 rifles a standard weapon for 
anc guerrillas 
