<TEXT>
an actors life is not easy but it certainly 
can be funny as tom mardirosian demonstrates in saved from 
obscurity his semiautobiographical play that opened thursday at 
offbroadways playwrights horizons 
mardirosian is a genial balding nondescript man one of those 
talented journeyman actors no one quite remembers when the house 
lights come up audiences occasionally see them in plays both on 
and offbroadway in television soap operas and if they dont 
blink in major motion pictures make no mistake theyll remember 
mardirosian after this 
he has put together a winning and ultimately joyous theatrical 
resume that celebrates his particular life in the theater for 90 
minutes the actor talks about his career and what lured a fat 
greekarmenian kid from buffalo ny to the stage 
was it his thwarted debut as the sheriff of nottingham in the 
fourth grade when his mother made him stay home from school because 
he was sick his understudy a girl yet went on to receive all 
the glory 
or was it beause of the funny faces he could make and get his 
friends a tough italian crowd to laugh out loud or his 
professional stage debut at buffalos studio arena in a bit role he 
got only because he could do a french accent 
mardirosian tells his story more or less chronologically with 
fine support from peter appel frederica meister and hansford rowe 
he highlights his work as an actor in new york and on the west 
coast 
the play has special appeal for theater buffs or insiders those 
audiences who actually have seen some of his quick flops such as 
cliffhanger offbroadway or happy end on broadway 
a high point of the evening is his explanation of his role in 
the normal heart larry kramers longrunning aids play in 
which the actor played several small parts among these was a 
doctor who sat silently on stage while being harangued by a fellow 
physician during the plays run mardirosian became bored in the 
role and began making up silent retorts to the accusations thrown 
at him 
the actor devotes a long segment to his association with cuba 
and his teddy bear the broadway play starring robert de niro and 
burt young mardirosian understudied both stars and finally went on 
one night for an absent young 
he takes the audience through his preparation to sub for the 
actor describing the terror and exhilaration of jumping into a 
play that is already running and working with actors who are used 
to performing with someone else its a fascinating story one that 
goes a long way toward explaining mardirosians enthusiasm for 
acting 
saved from obscurity the title refers to what the academy 
award did for the career of f murray abraham is the best kind of 
theater memoir its an inside story told by a pro with affection 
and just enough jaundice to make it all the more entertaining 
</TEXT>
