<TEXT>
to charles kuralt the charm of being on the 
road is that its such a little deal 
i just send back stories from the road about people i 
admire he said all these years cbs has let me do what i like 
i was in a little town in illinois where everyone has his name on a 
coffee cup down at the drug store when someone dies the cup comes 
down 
can you imagine that story being on the cbs evening news 
nobody makes a big deal about what i do thats the charm of 
it 
kuralt who has been doing little stories for cbs since 1967 is 
in good company charles dickens rudyard kipling and mark twain 
all took to the road and sent back little stories 
his latest journey into prime time is the onehour special 
back on the road with charles kuralt which cbs will telecast 
friday it takes him from duncan city ga to moscow the one in 
the soviet union 
with kuralt its necessary to distinguish between the soviets 
moscow and the smalltown moscows in idaho kansas missouri ohio 
pennsylvania and tennessee 
kuralt was in moscow for the summit when a burly old man bullied 
his way into his hotel and asked to speak to an american reporter 
his name was dr nikita zakaravich asseyev and he had been waiting 
43 years to tell his story 
his chest was covered with war medals and he intimidated the 
kgb men guarding the hotel kuralt said he told me he had been 
in a german prisoner of war camp in world war ii the russian 
prisoners were starving to death until american prisoners in 
another part of the camp began throwing their red cross food 
parcels over the fence 
dr asseyev had never forgotten the americans he had their 
names and he wanted to thank them for saving lives 
in the show kuralt talks to asseyev and then looks up the 
americans that the russian had remembered for so many years he 
found dr sidney brockman in san diego and william jarema a 
retired new york city police officer 
kuralts travels began in october 1967 when he persuaded cbs 
news to let him take a threemonth trial run he headed first for 
new england where he did a piece on the autumn leaves that was a 
revolutionary idea for the network news and gave kuralt the courage 
to do the hundreds of little stories that followed his reports 
have won two emmys two george foster peabody awards and a 
christopher award 
it helps if youre fat and bald said kuralt people look 
at me and say if that guy can be on tv so can i it helps put 
people at ease we dont come on like a bigtime television crew 
we keep it very low key i dont even appear in many of the 
stories 
kuralts cameraman is isadore bleckman his soundman is larry 
gianneschi jr and his coproducer is bernard birnbaum 
one rule that kuralt follows is that he never rides the 
tricycle 
we were watching a reporter cover a tricycle race for a local 
news show he said it was a good story until the end the 
newsman got on a tricycle and rode it it ruined the whole story 
kuralt says his trips on americas backroads have given him a 
different view of the country than one would get in the seats of 
power 
i have a much more sanguine view than you would get from 
reading the newspapers he said i think the country is in good 
shape i think things have changed for the better since i first 
went on the road i see candidates running for office as 
environmentalists twenty years ago no one would have dared to call 
himself an environmentalist people are much more aware and 
caring 
kuralt said his family grew used to his absences during his 
earlier years as a news correspondent in south america and los 
angeles 
when i was a little boy my dad had a traveling job he said 
i think thats where i got it my mother was a school teacher and 
my father was a social worker i used to go with him on his visits 
around north carolina 
these days he flies back to new york every weekend for his 
duties as host of cbs sunday morning 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
greater than 
elsewhere in television 
unsolved mysteries the murder of sports figure mickey 
thompson and his wife trudy last march will be reenacted for nbcs 
unsolved mysteries the couple was shot to death at their home 
in bradbury northeast of los angeles family spokesperson collene 
