<TEXT>
economic experts met thursday to 
discuss the ability of the united states to compete in the world 
marketplace but there was wide disagreement over whether the 
nation is falling behind its industrial competitors in asia and 
europe 
the huge us budget and foreign trade deficits were major 
issues in the debate 
as the elections approach a major question is the impact of 
american consumers buying more and more foreignmade products on 
our ability to deal with national priorities said harold j 
raveche president of stevens institute of technology which played 
host to the meeting 
let us also ask the difficult question how can a debtor 
nation continue to lead raveche said 
economist george gilder author of wealth and poverty and 
the spirit of enterprise countered that the supposed decline 
in us competitiveness is in fact a myth 
the key lesson of the past eight years is an overwhelming 
increase in us competitiveness that has attracted capital from 
all over the world he said 
gilder argued that the enormous us foreign trade deficits in 
recent years largely reflect the inflow of investment capital and 
are a sign of strength not of weakness 
it is ludicrous to worry about a foreign takeover of the 
united states economy when the united states still has 45 percent 
of the worlds foreign direct investment and when only five percent 
of american industrial assets are owned by foreigners compared to 
20 percent in europe he said 
david halberstam a pulitzer prizewinning author stressed the 
importance of education in world competitiveness noting that 
technical universities like stevens are the cutting edge of 
economic development 
peter sprague chairman of the board of national semiconductor 
corp noted that the american university system is a mecca for 
foreign students 
about half our science and engineering students are 
foreigners he said we should accept them as immigrants 
however halberstam argued that american primary and secondary 
education is inferior to the japanese system 
higher education in the united states will not be good enough 
if our elementary and high school education dont work he said 
the japanese are killing us in ninth grade mathematics 
kenneth wilson the 1982 winner of the nobel prize in physics 
urged the importance of government financing for scientific 
research he asserted that scientific progress in the united 
states for the past 30 years has been practically all financed by 
the government 
gilder emphatically held his position that the united states is 
surging ahead in competitiveness 
power has shifted and is shifting toward the united states and 
asia where more capitalist policies are followed he argued 
all europes growth in the 1980s was due to the growth of 
government consumption and created no new jobs at all europe is 
stagnating 
but clyde prestowitz jr former counselor for japanese affairs 
to the secretary of commerce took a gloomier view he recalled 
that successive american industries steel automobiles 
electronics semiconductors have failed to hold their own against 
japanese and other competitors 
now the japanese are increasing their foothold in us banking 
he said the competitiveness problem for the united states he 
said is not only industrial but also financial 
</TEXT>
